name: aws

attributes.name: default_tags
attributes.description:
You can assign metadata to your AWS resources in the form of tags.
Each tag is a label consisting of a user-defined key and value.
Tags can help you manage, identify, organize, search for, and filter resources.

attributes.name: tags
attributes.description: Key-value map of tags to apply to all resources.

attributes.name: ignore_tags
attributes.description:
Configuration block with resource tag settings to ignore across all resources handled by this provider
(except any individual service tag resources such as aws_ec2_tag)
for situations where external systems are managing certain resource tags.

attributes.name: keys
attributes.description: List of exact resource tag keys to ignore across all resources handled by this provider.

attributes.name: key_prefixes
attributes.description: List of resource tag key prefixes to ignore across all resources handled by this provider.

resources.description: An isolated database environment.

attributes.name: allow_major_version_upgrade
attributes.description: Indicates that major version upgrades are allowed.

attributes.description: Specifies whether any database modifications are applied immediately, or during the next maintenance window.

attributes.name: auto_minor_version_upgrade
attributes.description: Indicates that minor engine upgrades will be applied automatically to the DB instance during the maintenance window.

attributes.description: If 'Deletion protection' is set to true, the DB instance cannot be deleted. Otherwise, it can.

resources.description: A load balancer serves as the single point of contact for clients. The load balancer distributes incoming application traffic across multiple targets, in multiple Availability Zones.

attributes.name: vpc_id
attributes.description: The ID of the VPC to create the ALB in.

attributes.name: name
attributes.description:
The name of the LB. This name must be unique within your AWS account.
If not specified, Terraform will autogenerate a name beginning with tf-lb.

attributes.name: internal
attributes.description: If true, the LB will be internal.

attributes.name: load_balancer_type
attributes.description: The type of load balancer to create.

attributes.name: access_logs
attributes.description: An Access Logs block.

attributes.name: bucket
attributes.description: The S3 bucket name to store the logs in.

attributes.name: enabled
attributes.description: Boolean to enable / disable access_logs. Defaults to false, even when bucket is specified.

attributes.name: prefix
attributes.description: The S3 bucket prefix. Logs are stored in the root if not configured.

attributes.name: customer_owned_ipv4_pool
attributes.description: The ID of the customer owned ipv4 pool to use for this load balancer.

attributes.name: desync_mitigation_mode
attributes.description: Determines how the load balancer handles requests that might pose a security risk to an application due to HTTP desync.

attributes.name: drop_invalid_header_fields
attributes.description:
Indicates whether HTTP headers with header fields that are not valid are removed by the load balancer (true) or routed to targets (false).
The default is false. Elastic Load Balancing requires that message header names contain only alphanumeric characters and hyphens. Only valid for Load Balancers of type.

attributes.name: enable_cross_zone_load_balancing
attributes.description:
If true, cross-zone load balancing of the load balancer will be enabled. For network and gateway type load balancers, this feature is disabled by default (false).
For application load balancer this feature is always enabled (true) and cannot be disabled. Defaults to false.

attributes.name: enable_deletion_protection
attributes.description: If true, deletion of the load balancer will be disabled via the AWS API. This will prevent Terraform from deleting the load balancer. Defaults to false.

attributes.name: enable_http2
attributes.description: Indicates whether HTTP/2 is enabled in application load balancers. Defaults to true.

attributes.name: enable_waf_fail_open
attributes.description:
Indicates whether to allow a WAF-enabled load balancer to route requests to targets
if it is unable to forward the request to AWS WAF. Defaults to false.

attributes.name: idle_timeout
attributes.description:
The time in seconds that the connection is allowed to be idle.
Only valid for Load Balancers of type application. Default: 60.

attributes.name: ip_address_type
attributes.description: The type of IP addresses used by the subnets for your load balancer.

attributes.name: security_groups
attributes.description: A list of security group IDs to assign to the LB. Only valid for Load Balancers of type application.

attributes.name: preserve_host_header
attributes.description:
Indicates whether the Application Load Balancer should preserve the Host header in the HTTP request
and send it to the target without any change. Defaults to false.

attributes.name: subnet_mapping
attributes.description: A subnet mapping block.

attributes.name: subnet_id
attributes.description: ID of the subnet of which to attach to the load balancer. You can specify only one subnet per Availability Zone.

attributes.name: allocation_id
attributes.description: The allocation ID of the Elastic IP address for an internet-facing load balancer.

attributes.name: ipv6_address
attributes.description:
The IPv6 address. You associate IPv6 CIDR blocks with your VPC and choose the subnets
where you launch both internet-facing and internal Application Load Balancers or Network Load Balancers.

attributes.name: private_ipv4_address

resources.description:
Target groups route requests to one or more registered targets, using the protocol and port number that you specify.
You can register a target with multiple target groups

attributes.name: connection_termination
attributes.description: Whether to terminate connections at the end of the deregistration timeout on Network Load Balancers.

attributes.name: deregistration_delay
attributes.description: Amount time for Elastic Load Balancing to wait before changing the state of a deregistering target from draining to unused.

attributes.name: lambda_multi_value_headers_enabled
attributes.description: Whether the request and response headers exchanged between the load balancer and the Lambda function include arrays of values or strings.

attributes.name: load_balancing_algorithm_type
attributes.description: Determines how the load balancer selects targets when routing requests.

attributes.name: name
attributes.description: Name of the target group. If omitted, Terraform will assign a random, unique name.

attributes.name: name_prefix
attributes.description: Creates a unique name beginning with the specified prefix.

attributes.name: port

attributes.name: preserve_client_ip

attributes.name: protocol
attributes.description: Protocol to use for routing traffic to the targets.

attributes.name: protocol_version
attributes.description: Only applicable when protocol is HTTP or HTTPS. The protocol version.

attributes.name: proxy_protocol_v2
attributes.description: Whether to enable support for proxy protocol v2 on Network Load Balancers.

attributes.name: slow_start
attributes.description: Amount time for targets to warm up before the load balancer sends them a full share of requests.

attributes.name: target_type

attributes.name: ip_address_type

attributes.name: interval

attributes.name: matcher

attributes.name: path

attributes.name: protocol
attributes.description: The port the load balancer uses when performing health checks on targets.

attributes.name: timeout

attributes.name: stickiness

attributes.name: on_unhealthy
attributes.description: Indicates how the Gateway Load Balancer (GWLB) handles existing flows when a target is unhealthy.

resources.description:
A launch configuration is an instance configuration template that an Auto Scaling group uses to launch EC2 instances.
When you create a launch configuration, you specify information for the instances.

attributes.name: user_data

If you need to pass gzip-compressed data via this argument, use "user_data_base64" instead.

resources.description: Provides an Auto Scaling policy resource.

attributes.name: name
attributes.description: Name of the policy.

attributes.name: autoscaling_group_name
attributes.description: Name of the autoscaling group.

attributes.name: adjustment_type
attributes.description: Whether the adjustment is an absolute number or a percentage of the current capacity.

attributes.name: policy_type
attributes.description: Policy type

attributes.name: cooldown
attributes.description:
Amount of time, in seconds, after a scaling activity completes and before the next scaling activity can start.
Only available for SimpleScaling policies.

attributes.name: scaling_adjustment
attributes.description:
Number of instances by which to scale.
Only available for SimpleScaling policies.

attributes.name: estimated_instance_warmup
attributes.description: Estimated time, in seconds, until a newly launched instance can contribute to the CloudWatch metrics.

attributes.name: enabled
attributes.description: Whether the policy should be enabled.

attributes.name: min_adjustment_magnitude
attributes.description:
Minimum value to scale by when adjustment_type is set to PercentChangeInCapacity.
Only valid when policy_type is SimpleScaling or StepScalling.

attributes.name: metric_aggregation_type
attributes.description:
The aggregation type for the CloudWatch metrics.
Only valid when policy_type is StepScaling.

attributes.name: step_adjustment
attributes.description:
A list of step adjustments.
Only valid when policy_type is StepScaling.

attributes.name: metric_interval_lower_bound
attributes.description: The lower bound for the difference between the alarm threshold and the CloudWatch metric.

attributes.name: metric_interval_upper_bound
attributes.description: The upper bound for the difference between the alarm threshold and the CloudWatch metric.

attributes.name: scaling_adjustment
attributes.description: The number of members by which to scale.

resources.description: Watches a single metric over a specified time period, and performs one or more specified actions, based on the value of the metric relative to a threshold over time.

attributes.name: alarm_name
attributes.description: The descriptive name for the alarm. This name must be unique within the user's AWS account

attributes.name: comparison_operator
attributes.description: The arithmetic operation to use when comparing the specified Statistic and Threshold.

attributes.name: evaluation_periods
attributes.description: The number of periods over which data is compared to the specified threshold.

attributes.name: metric_name
attributes.description: The name for the alarm's associated metric.

attributes.name: namespace
attributes.description: The namespace for the alarm's associated metric.

attributes.name: period
attributes.description: The period in seconds over which the specified statistic is applied.

attributes.name: statistic
attributes.description: The statistic to apply to the alarm's associated metric.

attributes.name: threshold
attributes.description: The value against which the specified statistic is compared.

attributes.name: dimensions
attributes.description: The dimensions for the alarm's associated metric.

attributes.name: AutoScalingGroupName
attributes.description: Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling

attributes.name: actions_enabled
attributes.description: Indicates whether or not actions should be executed during any changes to the alarm's state.

attributes.name: alarm_description
attributes.description: The description for the alarm.

attributes.name: datapoints_to_alarm
attributes.description: The number of datapoints that must be breaching to trigger the alarm.

attributes.name: alarm_actions
attributes.description: The list of actions to execute when this alarm transitions into an ALARM state from any other state.

attributes.name: insufficient_data_actions
attributes.description: The list of actions to execute when this alarm transitions into an INSUFFICIENT_DATA state from any other state.

attributes.name: ok_actions
attributes.description: The list of actions to execute when this alarm transitions into an OK state from any other state.

attributes.name: unit
attributes.description: The unit for the alarm's associated metric.

attributes.name: extended_statistic
attributes.description: The percentile statistic for the metric associated with the alarm. Specify a value between p0.0 and p100.

attributes.name: treat_missing_data
attributes.description: Sets how this alarm is to handle missing data points.

attributes.name: evaluate_low_sample_count_percentiles
attributes.description:
Used only for alarms based on percentiles.
If ignore, the alarm state does not change during periods with too few data points to be statistically significant.
If evaluate or omit, the alarm is always evaluated and possibly changes state no matter how many data points are available.

attributes.name: metric_query
attributes.description: Enable to create an alarm based on a metric math expression.

attributes.name: id
attributes.description: A short name used to tie this object to the results in the response.

attributes.name: account_id
attributes.description: The account ID to use when searching for the metric.

attributes.name: expression
attributes.description: The math expression to be performed on the returned data, if this object is performing a math expression.

attributes.name: label
attributes.description: A human-readable label for this metric or expression.

attributes.name: return_data
attributes.description: Specify exactly one metric_query to be true to use that metric_query result as the alarm.
